const img = (name) => `/img/${name}`;

const article = (...sections) => sections.join("");

const practiceLab = ({ theme, deliverable, user, decision, failure, proof, growth }) => `
  <h2>Build-it-yourself lab: ${theme}</h2>
  <p>Reading about an engineering pattern is valuable, but building a small version makes it stay in memory. Create a focused project whose deliverable is <strong>${deliverable}</strong>. Keep the first version intentionally narrow. Your goal is not to add every possible feature; it is to deliver one complete path that a real ${user} could understand without explanation. Write the goal at the top of your README, list the main actions, and decide what “working” means before writing the polished UI.</p>
  <p>Begin by drawing the data and interaction flow on paper or in a short note. Identify what starts the process, what must be validated, what is stored or rendered, and what successful feedback the user sees. During this step, make an explicit architecture decision: ${decision}. Recording the decision matters because a project becomes easier to explain in interviews and easier to improve later. Good developers do not only present final screens; they can describe why the system was designed that way.</p>
  <p>Build the simplest complete version first. Use real sample content rather than lorem ipsum, keep components small, and connect only the actions needed for the core flow. Once it works, deliberately test the failure case: ${failure}. A product that succeeds under perfect input is a prototype. A product that responds clearly when something goes wrong starts to feel trustworthy. Add helpful error messaging, loading feedback, and an empty-state explanation before adding decorative polish.</p>
  <p>Now perform a quality pass. Test the page on a narrow mobile screen and a wide desktop display. Navigate by keyboard, verify readable contrast, confirm that buttons lead to valid destinations, and run a production build. If data changes, ensure the interface stays stable. If the feature includes asynchronous work, ensure the user understands whether it is loading, completed, or failed. Small checks are where professional confidence is built.</p>
  <p>Measure the result by asking: ${proof}. Avoid measuring quality only by the number of libraries used or how complex the code looks. The strongest evidence is a clear user flow, maintainable structure, a deployed demonstration, and an explanation of the tradeoffs you made. Screenshots show appearance; a working product shows ownership.</p>
  <p>After shipping the first version, write a short retrospective. Note one decision that worked, one point that caused confusion, one test you forgot at first, and one improvement you would add with another week. Your next growth step is ${growth}. Repeating this cycle across several focused projects builds much deeper skill than continually starting large unfinished ideas. The portfolio improves because every project carries a clear problem, a real solution, and a story about how you learned.</p>
`;

export const blogPosts = [
  {
    id: "1",
    title: "React 18 in Practice: Building Smooth Interfaces That Feel Fast",
    excerpt:
      "A practical guide to React 18 patterns for loading states, responsive interactions, component boundaries, and portfolio-quality frontends.",
    category: "React",
    date: "2026-01-15",
    readTime: "18 min read",
    image: img("blog-react.svg"),
    tags: ["React", "JavaScript", "Suspense", "Performance", "UI"],
    author: "Yasiru Nisal",
    content: article(
      `<p>React 18 is not only a version number. It changed how modern React applications can feel under pressure. A portfolio, dashboard, admin panel, ecommerce screen, or booking system may look beautiful in a screenshot, but the real test begins when the user types quickly, changes filters, opens a modal, waits for data, or moves between routes. That is where smooth interface engineering matters.</p>`,
      `<p>The biggest lesson I have learned while building React projects is that performance is not a single optimization at the end. It is a set of small decisions made across the whole interface. Component boundaries, state placement, loading design, image sizing, animation timing, and data-fetching strategy all work together. When these pieces are aligned, a React app feels calm, confident, and professional.</p>`,
      `<h2>Start with the user flow, not the component tree</h2>`,
      `<p>Before writing components, map the user flow. What does the user see first? What information do they need before making a decision? Which part of the page must feel instant? Which part can load later? For example, in an event booking website, the event title, date, venue, and booking button should appear quickly. Gallery images, related events, and extra animations can wait. In an admin dashboard, navigation, key metrics, and table controls matter first, while charts and secondary panels can be delayed.</p>`,
      `<p>This flow-first thinking prevents a common mistake: building one large component that tries to do everything. Large components often become difficult to maintain because UI state, data state, and styling logic all live together. A better approach is to create small sections with clear responsibilities. A hero section presents value. A filter panel changes data. A project card displays one item. A modal focuses attention. Each piece should be understandable on its own.</p>`,
      `<h2>Use concurrent-friendly thinking</h2>`,
      `<p>React 18 introduced better tools for handling updates without making the interface feel blocked. The idea is simple: not every update has the same priority. Typing in an input should feel immediate. Filtering a large list can be treated as less urgent. Navigation feedback should be fast. Expensive UI updates should not make the user wonder if the app is broken.</p>`,
      `<p>Even if a project is not using every advanced React API, the mindset is useful. Keep urgent state close to the interaction. Avoid recalculating big lists on every render. Use memoization only where it solves a real problem. Split views so slow areas do not freeze the whole screen. In practice, this means a search input can update its visible value immediately while the filtered result list updates a moment later in a smoother way.</p>`,
      `<pre><code>const visibleProjects = useMemo(() =&gt; {
  return projects.filter((project) =&gt;
    project.title.toLowerCase().includes(query.toLowerCase())
  );
}, [projects, query]);</code></pre>`,
      `<p>The code above is simple, but the principle is important. Derived data should be calculated deliberately. If a value can be derived from existing state, avoid storing it as another independent state variable unless there is a strong reason. This reduces bugs and keeps the component easier to reason about.</p>`,
      `<h2>Design loading states as part of the product</h2>`,
      `<p>A loading state is not an empty space. It is part of the user experience. In a premium interface, loading states should communicate that the app is alive and working. Skeleton cards, subtle shimmer, disabled buttons with text changes, and optimistic UI can all help. The key is restraint. Too much motion can feel cheap or distracting. A small pulse or blurred placeholder often feels more professional.</p>`,
      `<p>When building a React portfolio or SaaS-style dashboard, I like to design loading states before the final state is fully complete. This forces me to think about layout stability. If cards jump around after data loads, the page feels unstable. If image boxes reserve space before images appear, the page feels intentional. Layout stability is a design decision as much as a performance metric.</p>`,
      `<h2>Build components that accept content, not assumptions</h2>`,
      `<p>A reusable component should not know too much about one page. A card component can receive title, description, image, tags, and links. It should not hardcode one project. A section title component can receive eyebrow text, title, and description. It should not decide the entire page structure. This makes future redesigns much easier because the data and visual structure are separated.</p>`,
      `<p>For a portfolio, this is especially useful. Projects change. Skills grow. Blog posts expand. If the UI is driven by arrays of data, adding new work becomes safe and fast. It also keeps the design consistent. Every new project automatically gets the same spacing, border radius, image behavior, animation, and button style.</p>`,
      `<h2>Animation should support meaning</h2>`,
      `<p>Framer Motion is powerful, but the best animations are usually quiet. A section fading up when it enters the viewport gives the page rhythm. A card lifting on hover communicates clickability. A progress bar filling when visible tells the user that the information is active. Motion should guide attention, not compete with content.</p>`,
      `<p>For up-and-down scrolling, replayable viewport animations can make the site feel alive. The trick is to keep the distance small and the duration smooth. If every element flies across the screen, the user gets tired. A subtle movement from forty pixels below with opacity changing from zero to one is often enough. Premium UI is confident. It does not shout.</p>`,
      `<h2>Think in sections, then polish the edges</h2>`,
      `<p>After the main interface works, polish the edges. Check keyboard focus. Make anchor navigation smooth. Ensure the fixed navbar does not cover section headings. Test on mobile widths. Reduce oversized images. Hide buttons when there is no real link. These details make the difference between a project that looks finished and one that only looks designed.</p>`,
      `<h2>A practical React interface workflow</h2>`,
      `<p>When I begin a new interface, I first build the static layout with real content rather than placeholder words. Real names, real descriptions, real images, and realistic card counts reveal spacing problems early. Next I convert repeated content into data arrays and reusable components. Only after the interface works at mobile and desktop widths do I add Framer Motion transitions. This order prevents animation from hiding layout issues.</p>`,
      `<p>I also check the interface in stages. The first pass answers: is everything visible and readable? The second pass answers: does every interactive control work? The third pass answers: does the product feel polished? During the final pass, I test anchor navigation, external links, form validation, loading feedback, image fallbacks, empty filtering results, and reduced-motion support. A beautiful UI with one broken button can reduce trust quickly.</p>`,
      `<h2>Patterns worth practicing</h2>`,
      `<ul><li><strong>Filtered collections:</strong> Build a projects or articles grid driven by data and category buttons. It teaches derived state, memoization, empty states, and smooth layout animation.</li><li><strong>Reusable cards:</strong> Build one flexible card that handles image, tags, action links, and optional values. It teaches component APIs and content safety.</li><li><strong>Interactive forms:</strong> Build a contact or booking form with loading, success, and validation messages. It teaches state management and user feedback.</li><li><strong>Responsive navigation:</strong> Build a fixed desktop menu and animated mobile dropdown with active-section detection. It teaches accessibility and viewport behavior.</li></ul>`,
      `<p>For every pattern, ask one quality question: what happens when information is missing? A project without a live demo should not show a broken button. A card without an image needs a graceful fallback. A search with no results needs a useful message. A mobile menu should close after a link is chosen. Reliable interfaces are designed for imperfect situations, not only perfect screenshots.</p>`,
      `<h2>Performance checks before shipping</h2>`,
      `<p>Before deployment, inspect image sizes and load only what is necessary. Use lazy loading below the fold. Avoid rendering huge decorative effects on mobile. Check that the build completes cleanly and that links reach real destinations. If animations replay on scroll, keep them light enough that reading remains comfortable. If a page contains long articles, prioritize typography, line length, and contrast above visual tricks.</p>`,
      `<p>A useful performance mindset is to remove work before optimizing work. Do not add a heavy library when simple utilities solve the problem. Do not store unnecessary state. Do not render invisible sections repeatedly. Do not animate every element simply because motion is available. Performance and design meet in restraint: a responsive site feels premium because it lets the user move at their own speed.</p>`,
      `<h2>Workshop: turn a portfolio section into a product-quality feature</h2>`,
      `<p>Choose one real section, such as projects or blog posts, and treat it as a small product. Begin with a data model that includes every visible value: title, category, image, summary, technology tags, status, and valid action links. Render a grid from the array, then add filters. If a URL is missing, do not show an empty action. This simple rule immediately improves credibility because users never arrive at a dead button.</p>`,
      `<p>Now test content pressure. Use a very long project title, a missing image, six technology tags, and a narrow phone screen. The card should remain readable. Its buttons should wrap without overflowing. Its image area should preserve a stable shape. Real applications face uneven content, so this pressure test gives more confidence than designing only with perfectly short sample text.</p>`,
      `<p>Add motion last. Animate card entrance with opacity and a small upward movement. Use layout animation for filtering so cards rearrange smoothly rather than jumping. Add a light hover lift only for pointer devices. Then revisit the section while scrolling both down and up. Motion should repeat gracefully without hiding content from a reader who moves quickly. If it starts to feel theatrical rather than helpful, reduce it.</p>`,
      `<p>Finally, test the feature as a visitor would: arrive from the navbar, filter a category, open a working link, return to the page, scan content on a mobile viewport, and use keyboard navigation. This is how a visual React section becomes a dependable interface. Beautiful components attract attention; careful behavior earns confidence.</p>`,
      practiceLab({
        theme: "an animated React project gallery",
        deliverable: "a responsive gallery with categories, usable links, image fallbacks, and calm viewport animations",
        user: "portfolio visitor",
        decision: "keep project information in data arrays and reusable card components rather than hardcoding individual cards",
        failure: "a project has no screenshot or live URL, or filtering returns no matches",
        proof: "can a visitor find a relevant build, understand its purpose, and open a real destination without friction?",
        growth: "adding tested form interactions or route transitions while respecting reduced-motion preferences",
      }),
      `<p>React 18 gives developers the foundation for smoother interfaces, but the real craft is in how we combine architecture, loading states, motion, and content. A good React app should feel responsive, readable, and maintainable. When the code is clean and the interface is calm, users trust the product faster.</p>`
    ),
  },
  {
    id: "2",
    title: "MERN vs Next.js: Choosing the Right Stack for Real Projects",
    excerpt:
      "A practical comparison of MERN and Next.js for client sites, dashboards, content platforms, SEO, deployments, and long-term maintainability.",
    category: "Web Development",
    date: "2026-01-10",
    readTime: "20 min read",
    image: img("blog-architecture.svg"),
    tags: ["MERN", "Next.js", "Node.js", "Architecture"],
    author: "Yasiru Nisal",
    content: article(
      `<p>Choosing a stack is not about picking the most popular technology. It is about choosing the best path for the product, the team, and the user. MERN and Next.js are both strong choices, but they solve slightly different problems. If you understand those differences, you can make better technical decisions and avoid rebuilding later.</p>`,
      `<p>MERN usually means MongoDB, Express.js, React, and Node.js. It gives a clear separation between frontend and backend. Next.js is a React framework that can handle routing, rendering, API endpoints, server components, static generation, and deployment workflows in a more integrated way. Both can build modern products. The right choice depends on what the product needs most.</p>`,
      `<h2>When MERN is a strong choice</h2>`,
      `<p>MERN works well when the application has a clear API layer and a frontend that consumes that API. Admin dashboards, management systems, custom business tools, and data-driven apps are common examples. Express gives you full control over routing, middleware, authentication, validation, and database access. MongoDB gives flexibility when the data shape changes often.</p>`,
      `<p>If you are building a system where the backend may later serve mobile apps, desktop apps, or multiple frontend clients, a separate Node and Express API can be useful. The API becomes a product of its own. This separation can also make team collaboration cleaner: one person can focus on backend routes and database models while another person builds the React interface.</p>`,
      `<p>The tradeoff is that MERN requires more decisions. You must decide how to handle routing, bundling, SEO, deployment, environment variables, caching, validation, and folder structure. This flexibility is powerful, but it can slow down smaller projects if every decision needs to be designed from scratch.</p>`,
      `<h2>When Next.js is a strong choice</h2>`,
      `<p>Next.js is excellent when the website needs strong page structure, SEO, fast loading, and a smooth deployment path. Business websites, landing pages, blogs, documentation sites, portfolios, and content platforms often benefit from Next.js. The framework gives you routing, rendering strategies, image optimization options, metadata handling, and production-minded conventions.</p>`,
      `<p>For content-heavy projects, Next.js can be especially practical. A blog platform can pre-render pages, load quickly, and still include interactive client components where needed. A business website can ship marketing pages and contact forms without requiring a separate frontend application. A portfolio can combine static content, animations, and dynamic-looking UI while staying deployable.</p>`,
      `<p>Next.js does not remove backend thinking. It simply changes where some backend behavior lives. You can build API routes, server actions, or connect to external services. You can still use MongoDB, PostgreSQL, Firebase, or REST APIs. The benefit is that many full-stack concerns are closer to the page that uses them.</p>`,
      `<h2>Compare based on product needs</h2>`,
      `<p>If the product is a business website, company site, blog, portfolio, or SEO-focused content product, Next.js is usually the faster and cleaner choice. If the product is an internal system with complex backend logic, many custom APIs, and multiple clients, MERN can be a strong fit. If the product is a hybrid, Next.js can still work, but you may choose to connect it to a separate backend service.</p>`,
      `<p>For example, an event booking website can be built either way. If it is mostly a public website with ticket discovery, SEO pages, and a contact flow, Next.js is attractive. If it has a deep admin dashboard, complex reservation logic, and external integrations, a separate backend may be useful. The best architecture is the one that keeps future changes easy.</p>`,
      `<h2>Authentication and dashboards</h2>`,
      `<p>Dashboards require careful planning. You need protected routes, user sessions, role checks, forms, tables, loading states, and error handling. MERN gives you direct backend control for JWT or session-based auth. Next.js gives you route-level structure and server-side patterns. Neither choice automatically makes auth simple. The important part is designing a clear permission model and keeping sensitive logic away from the browser.</p>`,
      `<p>For portfolio projects and small client work, avoid overengineering. If a site only needs a contact form, do not build a complex backend. If an admin panel only needs limited access for one business owner, keep the flow simple and secure. Good engineering means choosing enough architecture, not the biggest architecture.</p>`,
      `<h2>Deployment and maintenance</h2>`,
      `<p>Next.js has a strong advantage when deployment speed matters. Platforms like Vercel make it easy to connect a repository and ship updates quickly. MERN often requires deploying the frontend and backend separately, configuring environment variables in two places, and managing CORS or API domains. That is not bad, but it is more operational work.</p>`,
      `<p>Maintenance also depends on team skill. A clean MERN codebase can be easier to understand than a messy Next.js app. A well-structured Next.js app can be faster to ship than a scattered MERN project. The framework does not replace discipline. Naming, folder structure, reusable components, error boundaries, and consistent data handling still matter.</p>`,
      `<h2>My practical rule</h2>`,
      `<p>For websites, portfolios, blogs, company pages, and content products, I usually lean toward Next.js. For management systems, API-heavy applications, or products that need a separate backend service, I consider MERN or a Next.js frontend connected to a dedicated API. For small projects, I choose the stack that gets the product live with the least unnecessary complexity.</p>`,
      `<h2>Architecture questions to ask before choosing</h2>`,
      `<p>Start by writing down the pages and roles in the product. Does it have only public pages, or does it need an authenticated admin dashboard? Will search engines need to discover content? Does it need scheduled publishing? Will there be a mobile client later? Does the business owner need reporting or inventory? These questions are more useful than asking which stack is trendy.</p>`,
      `<p>Next, consider data ownership. If a dedicated API must be consumed by several clients, separating the backend makes sense. If data is mainly used by one website, an integrated Next.js application can reduce complexity. Then consider deployment skills and budget. A small business should not pay operational costs for unnecessary architecture. Simplicity is not a weakness when it meets the requirements reliably.</p>`,
      `<h2>Example decisions for real portfolio products</h2>`,
      `<ul><li><strong>Company website:</strong> Next.js is usually enough because pages require speed, search visibility, metadata, and contact actions more than a large API.</li><li><strong>Automated blog platform:</strong> Next.js works well with content routes and deployment workflows, while automation can run through scheduled jobs or repository workflows.</li><li><strong>POS desktop system:</strong> The desktop application may use Electron or .NET with SQLite; its marketing/download site can still use a small web frontend.</li><li><strong>Booking dashboard:</strong> A modern frontend paired with protected server logic is essential because reservations and administration require trustworthy data flows.</li></ul>`,
      `<h2>Team and portfolio learning value</h2>`,
      `<p>MERN exposes the shape of a backend clearly. You learn controllers, middleware, authentication, database queries, API contracts, CORS, and error handling. Next.js exposes production web concerns clearly. You learn routing, rendering decisions, server and client boundaries, metadata, content delivery, loading UI, and deployment structure. Building projects in both ecosystems gives you a better engineering vocabulary.</p>`,
      `<p>When presenting projects in a portfolio, explain why the stack suited the product. “Built with Next.js” is less powerful than “used Next.js for a fast, deployable company website with responsive service pages.” “Built with MERN” is less powerful than “designed a separate API and dashboard for management workflows.” Technology becomes impressive when connected to a real outcome.</p>`,
      `<h2>Migration and future growth</h2>`,
      `<p>The first stack choice does not permanently lock a product. A static business site can later gain an authenticated dashboard. A Next.js app can later consume a dedicated service. A MERN frontend can migrate to a framework that improves content rendering. The important preparation is keeping data boundaries clean, avoiding duplicated business rules, and writing maintainable components and APIs.</p>`,
      `<p>Choose the simplest structure that supports the present product and leaves a reasonable path for the future. That balance is professional architecture: not predicting every possibility, but not making tomorrow unnecessarily painful.</p>`,
      `<h2>Workshop: decide a stack for a new client idea</h2>`,
      `<p>Imagine a small business requests a website with service pages, gallery, inquiry form, owner dashboard, and future blog posts. Begin by separating requirements into public pages, authenticated features, data storage, integrations, and future ideas. The public marketing experience benefits from fast initial pages and metadata. The dashboard requires protected operations. The blog may later benefit from structured content and automation.</p>`,
      `<p>A reasonable first architecture could be a Next.js application for public pages and dashboard routes, connected to secure server-side data operations. This keeps deployment manageable while the product is young. If the business later needs a mobile application or complex integrations, extract stable business operations behind a dedicated API. This avoids starting with unnecessary complexity but does not ignore growth.</p>`,
      `<p>Now compare that with MERN. If the owner already requires many admin modules, multiple employee roles, inventory operations, mobile consumption, and detailed reporting, an Express API may provide clearer ownership for business logic. A React dashboard can consume that API, and public pages can be served separately or with an SEO-capable frontend. Neither answer is universally correct; the requirements make one answer more sensible.</p>`,
      `<p>Document your decision in the project README: what the product solves, why you chose the architecture, what data it handles, how it is deployed, and what you would add next. That explanation demonstrates engineering maturity. It also makes future changes easier because you can judge whether the original assumptions are still true.</p>`,
      `<h2>A final comparison checklist</h2>`,
      `<ul><li>Choose Next.js when public content, SEO, integrated routing, fast deployments, and a single product codebase are major priorities.</li><li>Choose a separate API architecture when multiple clients, complex permissions, rich business logic, or backend independence are major priorities.</li><li>Choose based on maintainability and delivery, not on which technology looks most impressive in a badge list.</li><li>Whatever the stack, test builds, secure secrets, validate input, and explain the product outcome clearly.</li></ul>`,
      practiceLab({
        theme: "a stack decision prototype",
        deliverable: "a small business landing page with a protected content-management concept and documented architecture choices",
        user: "business owner",
        decision: "state whether a unified Next.js application or a React client with a separate Node API better serves the real requirements",
        failure: "a future feature requires server data or administration that the initial static design did not anticipate",
        proof: "does the selected stack let the product launch quickly while keeping the next realistic feature manageable?",
        growth: "building the same feature once with an integrated framework and once with a separated API to compare maintenance honestly",
      }),
      `<p>The best stack is the one that helps you ship, learn, maintain, and improve. MERN teaches backend fundamentals clearly. Next.js teaches modern full-stack React workflows. A strong developer should understand both, then choose intentionally.</p>`
    ),
  },
  {
    id: "3",
    title: "CI/CD Basics for Modern Web Apps: From Git Push to Reliable Deploy",
    excerpt:
      "A builder-friendly explanation of automated tests, builds, deployment workflows, environment checks, and safer release habits.",
    category: "Projects",
    date: "2026-01-05",
    readTime: "19 min read",
    image: img("blog-cicd.svg"),
    tags: ["CI/CD", "GitHub Actions", "DevOps", "Deployment"],
    author: "Yasiru Nisal",
    content: article(
      `<p>CI/CD sounds advanced until you break it down. Continuous Integration means checking your code automatically when changes are pushed. Continuous Deployment means shipping approved changes automatically or semi-automatically. For modern web projects, this can be the difference between a stressful release and a confident workflow.</p>`,
      `<p>Every developer eventually experiences the same problem: code works locally, but fails in production. Maybe an environment variable is missing. Maybe the build command fails. Maybe a dependency version changed. Maybe a teammate pushed a change that broke another page. CI/CD reduces these surprises by making the project prove itself before it is deployed.</p>`,
      `<h2>The simplest useful pipeline</h2>`,
      `<p>A lightweight pipeline can have only three steps: install dependencies, run quality checks, and build the project. If those steps pass, the project is likely deployable. You can add tests, linting, formatting checks, type checking, preview deployments, and production deployment later. Start simple, then improve as the project grows.</p>`,
      `<pre><code>name: Build Check
on: [push, pull_request]
jobs:
  build:
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest
    steps:
      - uses: actions/checkout@v4
      - uses: actions/setup-node@v4
        with:
          node-version: 20
      - run: npm install
      - run: npm run build</code></pre>`,
      `<p>This basic workflow already catches many problems. If the project cannot install or build in a clean environment, it should not be deployed. A clean environment is important because your local machine may contain cached packages, hidden files, or environment settings that production does not have.</p>`,
      `<h2>Use branches as safety zones</h2>`,
      `<p>For personal projects, pushing directly to main is common. For client projects or professional work, branches create safer collaboration. A feature branch lets you build a change without disturbing the deployed version. A pull request creates a review point. CI can run on the pull request before the change merges. This creates a habit of confidence.</p>`,
      `<p>Branch discipline does not need to be complicated. Use main for stable code, feature branches for work in progress, and clear commit messages. If a deployment breaks, you can understand what changed. If a feature needs to be paused, it can stay in its branch. This is especially useful when working on multiple client changes at once.</p>`,
      `<h2>Environment variables must be treated carefully</h2>`,
      `<p>Most real apps use secrets: API keys, database URLs, email tokens, analytics IDs, or webhook secrets. These should not be committed to GitHub. A CI/CD pipeline should read them from the deployment platform or repository secrets. This keeps sensitive information outside the source code.</p>`,
      `<p>A common mistake is forgetting to configure the same variable in production. The build passes locally because <code>.env.local</code> exists, but production fails because the value is missing. A good release checklist includes environment variables. A better pipeline can validate required variables before deployment.</p>`,
      `<h2>Automated deployment for content platforms</h2>`,
      `<p>Automated publishing becomes powerful when content is generated or scheduled. A blog platform can create an article file, commit it to GitHub, and trigger deployment. This turns publishing into a repeatable workflow. The site becomes easier to maintain because new content follows the same path every time.</p>`,
      `<p>For a content automation product, the pipeline is part of the product experience. The user may not see GitHub Actions, build logs, or deployment hooks, but they feel the result: content appears on schedule. Reliability matters more than flashy UI. If scheduled content fails silently, trust disappears. Logs, status messages, and fallback behavior are important.</p>`,
      `<h2>Preview deployments reduce fear</h2>`,
      `<p>Preview deployments are one of the best habits for modern frontend work. Before merging a change, you can open a live preview URL and test the exact UI in a browser. This is useful for responsive design, animations, forms, images, and real-world loading behavior. Screenshots are helpful, but clicking the preview is better.</p>`,
      `<p>For client work, preview deployments also improve communication. Instead of explaining a change with screenshots only, you can send a temporary preview link. The client can test the flow and give feedback before production changes. That saves time and reduces misunderstandings.</p>`,
      `<h2>Do not automate broken habits</h2>`,
      `<p>CI/CD does not fix messy code by itself. If the project has no clear scripts, no build command, no environment rules, and no review habit, automation may only move chaos faster. First make the local workflow reliable. Then automate it. The pipeline should reflect the way a good developer already checks their work.</p>`,
      `<h2>A deployment checklist that scales</h2>`,
      `<p>A useful deployment checklist begins before code reaches the repository. Confirm that the feature works locally, that forms show meaningful failure messages, that images and external links resolve, and that responsive layouts do not overflow. Run the same build command the platform will run. Commit only the files the feature requires. Then push and watch the automated result rather than assuming success.</p>`,
      `<ul><li>Verify required environment values exist in the hosting platform and do not appear in source control.</li><li>Run install, lint or validation checks, and the production build in a clean environment.</li><li>Test preview links on desktop and mobile before production merge.</li><li>Keep release commits readable enough to revert or understand during an incident.</li><li>Check the deployed application after release, especially form submissions and content routes.</li></ul>`,
      `<h2>Handling failure professionally</h2>`,
      `<p>Failures are normal; invisible failures are dangerous. If a scheduled blog publication fails, the workflow should expose which step failed. If a build fails because content data is invalid, the log should be clear enough to fix quickly. If deployment succeeds but a live endpoint breaks, monitoring and a rollback path matter. Professional delivery is not pretending nothing fails. It is recovering predictably.</p>`,
      `<p>A small project can use simple recovery habits: keep the last stable commit, do not delete old deployments immediately, test live links after publishing, and record required environment variables. For a larger project, add branch protections, required checks, deployment environments, review permissions, and status notifications. The practices grow with risk.</p>`,
      `<h2>CI/CD as a portfolio skill</h2>`,
      `<p>Many portfolios display only screenshots and technology badges. Showing delivery knowledge makes projects stronger. If you built a site that publishes scheduled articles automatically, describe that workflow. If a downloadable desktop product has a release page, explain how users receive builds. If a client website is deployed live, explain the production outcome. Shipping is part of software engineering.</p>`,
      `<p>An excellent project description can say: I designed the interface, connected the content model, configured automated builds, and deployed updates through a repeatable workflow. That statement communicates ownership beyond UI construction. It tells employers and clients that you understand how code becomes a reliable product.</p>`,
      `<h2>Improve one pipeline at a time</h2>`,
      `<p>Start by automating the command you already trust: the production build. Next add quality checks. Later add previews, scheduled content generation, deployment gates, notifications, and release notes. Each improvement should reduce a real risk or manual task. A pipeline is useful when it gives you time and confidence, not when it becomes a second complicated product to maintain.</p>`,
      `<h2>Workshop: build a release workflow for a small product</h2>`,
      `<p>Suppose you have built a public website that regularly receives design updates and content additions. Start by defining the safe release path in plain language: development happens in a branch, a pull request triggers a build check, a preview URL is reviewed, and merging to main triggers production deployment. This statement is the workflow before it becomes configuration.</p>`,
      `<p>Next, decide what a successful check proves. For a modern frontend, a production build confirms routes and bundled assets compile. A lint or type check catches common code errors. A quick manual preview confirms typography, links, responsive navigation, and contact forms. For an automated content site, add validation that generated article metadata is present and that scheduled entries contain required fields before publishing.</p>`,
      `<p>Store secrets outside the repository. A form API key, deployment token, or automation credential should live in configured secrets, not in public JavaScript or committed environment files. Limit which workflow actions may access those values. If a secret changes, document where it must be updated. Operational clarity prevents a deployment problem from becoming a security problem.</p>`,
      `<p>When release day comes, read the workflow output. A green badge is useful, but knowing what it checked is better. Open the live site after deployment, validate the newest changed paths, and retain a quick rollback route. For a downloadable Windows POS product, confirm the download button and version information. For a blog automation product, confirm the published post appears at the correct route and is shareable.</p>`,
      `<h2>Signals of a professional pipeline</h2>`,
      `<ul><li>A new contributor can learn how to deploy from the repository documentation.</li><li>A failed build stops an unsafe deployment rather than publishing broken work.</li><li>Preview testing catches layout and content issues before customers see them.</li><li>Scheduled automation reports failures visibly instead of silently missing releases.</li><li>The team knows how to restore a previous stable version when needed.</li></ul>`,
      practiceLab({
        theme: "a safe deployment pipeline",
        deliverable: "a deployed web application with a branch-based build check, preview validation checklist, and release notes",
        user: "site owner awaiting an update",
        decision: "define which checks must pass before a commit can reach the production deployment branch",
        failure: "the build fails, an environment value is missing, or a scheduled publish job produces invalid content",
        proof: "can you detect failure before users see it and restore a stable release without guessing?",
        growth: "adding deployment reporting and content validation to an automated publishing workflow",
      }),
      `<p>Keep a short deployment runbook beside the project as well. Document which branch reaches production, which secrets are required, how a teammate can confirm the live version, and what rollback action is safe. This turns CI/CD from an invisible button into shared engineering knowledge. It also makes client work easier to hand over because future updates do not depend on one developer remembering every setup detail.</p>`,
      `<p>My preferred release habit is simple: write the feature, test locally, run the build, push to a branch, let CI verify, check the preview, then deploy. This rhythm works for portfolios, business websites, SaaS dashboards, content platforms, and client products. It creates calm releases, which is exactly what professional software delivery should feel like.</p>`
    ),
  },
  {
    id: "4",
    title: "Clean API Design for Scalable Products",
    excerpt:
      "How to design REST APIs with predictable routes, validation, status codes, error messages, and frontend-friendly responses.",
    category: "Backend",
    date: "2025-12-28",
    readTime: "17 min read",
    image: img("blog-api.svg"),
    tags: ["REST", "Express", "Architecture", "Backend"],
    author: "Yasiru Nisal",
    content: article(
      `<p>A clean API is invisible when it works well. The frontend developer can request data, send forms, handle errors, and build features without fighting unclear responses. The backend developer can add routes without breaking old behavior. The product owner gets a system that can grow. That is why API design matters.</p>`,
      `<p>Many beginner APIs start as quick route handlers. A route is created when a page needs data. Another route is added for a form. Another is added for an admin action. This works for a small project, but it becomes hard to maintain when naming, validation, error handling, and response shapes are inconsistent. Clean design keeps the API understandable.</p>`,
      `<h2>Use resources as the foundation</h2>`,
      `<p>REST APIs work best when routes are based on resources. A resource is usually a noun: users, projects, orders, bookings, posts, products, tickets. Actions are represented through HTTP methods. GET reads. POST creates. PATCH updates. DELETE removes. This gives the API a predictable language.</p>`,
      `<pre><code>GET    /api/bookings
POST   /api/bookings
GET    /api/bookings/:id
PATCH  /api/bookings/:id
DELETE /api/bookings/:id</code></pre>`,
      `<p>There are exceptions, but start with this pattern. It makes frontend code easier because developers can guess route behavior. It also makes documentation easier. If every resource follows the same style, a new teammate can learn the API faster.</p>`,
      `<h2>Design response shapes deliberately</h2>`,
      `<p>A response should be predictable. If one route returns { data: ... } and another returns the raw object and another returns { result: ... }, frontend code becomes messy. Choose a shape and use it consistently. For many projects, a simple structure works well: success, data, message, and optional error details.</p>`,
      `<pre><code>{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Booking created successfully.",
  "data": {
    "id": "booking_123",
    "status": "confirmed"
  }
}</code></pre>`,
      `<p>Error responses deserve the same care. A useful error tells the frontend what happened without exposing sensitive internals. “Invalid input” is better than a database stack trace. “Email is required” is better than a generic failure. Good error messages reduce debugging time and improve user experience.</p>`,
      `<h2>Validate before touching the database</h2>`,
      `<p>Validation protects the database and improves reliability. Required fields, email format, numeric ranges, date rules, file sizes, and enum values should be checked before the main business logic runs. This keeps route handlers cleaner and prevents invalid data from entering the system.</p>`,
      `<p>Validation is also a product decision. For example, an event booking API should validate ticket quantities, available seats, event dates, customer email, and payment state. A POS API should validate product price, stock quantity, invoice totals, and transaction state. These rules are not only technical. They protect the business process.</p>`,
      `<h2>Status codes communicate intent</h2>`,
      `<p>HTTP status codes help clients understand what happened. Use <code>200</code> for successful reads, <code>201</code> for successful creation, <code>400</code> for invalid input, <code>401</code> for unauthenticated requests, <code>403</code> for forbidden actions, <code>404</code> for missing resources, and <code>500</code> for unexpected server problems. You do not need to memorize every code, but common codes should be used consistently.</p>`,
      `<p>When status codes and response messages match, frontend error handling becomes cleaner. The UI can show validation messages for 400 responses, redirect login for 401 responses, and show a fallback screen for 500 responses. The API and UI become a team.</p>`,
      `<h2>Keep controllers focused</h2>`,
      `<p>A route handler should not become a giant file. Split responsibilities when logic grows. Routes define endpoints. Controllers handle request and response flow. Services contain business logic. Database models handle persistence. Middleware handles authentication and validation. This separation is not required for tiny apps, but it becomes valuable quickly.</p>`,
      `<p>Good structure makes testing easier. A service function can be tested without starting a server. Validation middleware can be reused. Auth logic can protect many routes. When a bug appears, you know where to look. This is the difference between a backend that works once and a backend that can grow.</p>`,
      `<h2>Document the behavior users depend on</h2>`,
      `<p>API documentation does not need to be huge. A simple README section with routes, request bodies, response examples, and environment variables is enough for many projects. For bigger systems, use API collections or generated docs. The goal is to make integration clear.</p>`,
      `<h2>Pagination, filtering, and query design</h2>`,
      `<p>Once an application has many records, returning everything in one request is no longer helpful. Projects with bookings, orders, products, or blog posts need pagination and filtering. A route such as <code>GET /api/orders?page=2&amp;limit=20&amp;status=paid</code> allows the frontend to request only what it needs. The API should validate query values, define defaults, and include paging metadata in the response.</p>`,
      `<p>Filtering must also protect performance. If users search often, decide which fields are searchable and how results are ordered. If an admin dashboard sorts by date or status, keep that behavior consistent. The frontend should not have to guess whether the backend sorts newest-first or oldest-first. Small API agreements eliminate large UI confusion.</p>`,
      `<h2>Authentication is not authorization</h2>`,
      `<p>Authentication asks who the user is. Authorization asks what that user may do. A logged-in customer should not be able to call an admin deletion endpoint. A content editor might publish articles but not manage payments. A business owner may view reports that staff cannot. These rules belong on the server, not only in hidden buttons on the frontend.</p>`,
      `<p>For every protected action, verify identity and permission before applying changes. Avoid returning sensitive fields when they are not needed. Avoid trusting values supplied by the client for price, role, status, or ownership. A frontend is a user experience layer; the backend is where trust must be enforced.</p>`,
      `<h2>API quality checklist for a product build</h2>`,
      `<ul><li>Name endpoints with consistent resource nouns and method behavior.</li><li>Validate request bodies and query parameters before database operations.</li><li>Return predictable success and error structures with suitable status codes.</li><li>Keep secrets, permissions, and sensitive business logic on the server.</li><li>Log unexpected failures safely without exposing private internals to the client.</li><li>Document the routes a teammate or future version of the product will use.</li></ul>`,
      `<h2>Testing through the frontend and Postman</h2>`,
      `<p>A backend should be tested directly and through its user interface. Postman or a similar API tool helps you confirm route behavior, request bodies, authorization headers, errors, and edge cases without depending on frontend code. The UI then confirms that real users see correct feedback. Test success paths, invalid input, missing data, unauthorized requests, and server failures where possible.</p>`,
      `<p>This approach is valuable for internship work and personal products alike. It demonstrates that you can build a feature across the whole flow: database behavior, API contract, UI interaction, and testing. That full-stack understanding is more useful than simply connecting a form to an endpoint once.</p>`,
      `<h2>Workshop: design an event booking API</h2>`,
      `<p>Consider an event website where visitors view an event and reserve tickets while an administrator manages availability. The primary resources might be events, bookings, customers, and users. A visitor can read published events and create a booking. An administrator can update event details, see bookings, and manage status. Writing these capabilities first makes endpoint design clearer.</p>`,
      `<p>A booking creation request should include the event identifier, customer contact information, and ticket quantity. The server should validate that the event exists, is open for booking, has enough remaining availability, and receives sensible contact information. It should calculate any protected totals on the server rather than trusting totals sent by the browser. When creation succeeds, return a clear booking identifier and status that the UI can display.</p>`,
      `<p>An admin listing route should be protected by authorization and support filters such as event, booking status, search term, and date range. The response should include pagination metadata so the dashboard can render page controls consistently. A status update endpoint should validate allowed transitions so a cancelled booking is not accidentally confirmed without business approval.</p>`,
      `<p>Test the API before polishing the dashboard. Create a valid booking, create one with missing email, request an unknown event, exceed ticket availability, access an admin endpoint without permission, and change booking status. Then connect the frontend. When the API behavior is already predictable, UI feedback becomes far easier to design and debug.</p>`,
      `<h2>What good backend work communicates</h2>`,
      `<ul><li>The API protects business rules, not only data storage.</li><li>Frontend developers receive consistent data and actionable errors.</li><li>Administrative operations are protected and traceable.</li><li>Future features such as payment, email notification, or reporting have stable foundations.</li></ul>`,
      practiceLab({
        theme: "a booking API and admin flow",
        deliverable: "a documented REST API with validated booking creation, protected management routes, and frontend-readable errors",
        user: "customer making a reservation",
        decision: "keep pricing, availability checks, permissions, and booking-status rules on the server",
        failure: "a request has invalid fields, requests unavailable capacity, or attempts an admin action without permission",
        proof: "does every API response help the frontend guide the user correctly while protecting business rules?",
        growth: "adding automated endpoint tests and role-based administration to the working API contract",
      }),
      `<p>A compact API example collection is a strong finishing touch. Include one successful booking request, one validation error, one protected admin request, and one paginated response. This helps another developer integrate the interface without reading every controller first. It also helps you test changes quickly: when the data contract evolves, run the same examples and confirm that status codes, error messages, and response fields still guide the UI correctly. Clear examples also become a faster onboarding guide when a new teammate joins the product.</p>`,
      `<p>Clean API design is about respect for future work. The future developer may be another teammate, a client, or your own tired self three months later. Predictable routes, consistent responses, validation, and useful errors make software easier to maintain. That is the kind of backend quality users may never see directly, but they benefit from every day.</p>`
    ),
  },
  {
    id: "5",
    title: "Learning AI Integration in Web Apps Without Overcomplicating It",
    excerpt:
      "A practical path for adding AI features to products through clear use cases, safe workflows, useful prompts, and simple automation.",
    category: "AI",
    date: "2025-12-15",
    readTime: "18 min read",
    image: img("blog-ai.svg"),
    tags: ["AI", "Python", "Automation", "Product"],
    author: "Yasiru Nisal",
    content: article(
      `<p>AI integration is most useful when it solves a clear product problem. It should not be added only because it sounds modern. A strong AI feature saves time, improves decision-making, helps users create something, summarizes complexity, recommends a next step, or automates a repetitive workflow. If the feature does not do one of those things, it may become decoration instead of value.</p>`,
      `<p>The best way to learn AI integration is to start small. Build one feature that takes input, sends it to an AI service, receives a response, and displays that response in a useful format. Then improve the prompt, add validation, store results, and create a better user flow. This teaches the full cycle without overwhelming the project.</p>`,
      `<h2>Start with a real use case</h2>`,
      `<p>A use case should be specific. “Add AI” is not specific. “Generate blog post ideas for freelance designers” is specific. “Summarize interview answers and suggest improvements” is specific. “Rewrite a product description in a friendly tone” is specific. The more specific the use case, the easier it is to design the UI and prompt.</p>`,
      `<p>For example, PromptEarn can focus on beginner-friendly AI income ideas. The AI feature is not just text generation. It supports a content workflow: choose a topic, generate a structured article, review it, schedule it, publish it, and deploy the site. That is a product workflow, not just a prompt box.</p>`,
      `<h2>Design the prompt like an interface</h2>`,
      `<p>A prompt is part of the product. It should include role, task, context, constraints, output format, and quality expectations. If the output needs headings, bullets, examples, or JSON, say so clearly. If the tone must be beginner-friendly, say that. If the answer should avoid unsupported claims, include that rule.</p>`,
      `<pre><code>Write a beginner-friendly article outline.
Audience: students learning web development.
Topic: React project structure.
Output: title, intro, 5 sections, conclusion.
Tone: practical, clear, encouraging.
Avoid: fake statistics and unsupported promises.</code></pre>`,
      `<p>Prompt design is iterative. The first response may be too generic. Instead of blaming the model, improve the instruction. Add examples. Tighten the output format. Ask for practical steps. Tell it what not to include. AI features become better when the developer treats prompts as product logic.</p>`,
      `<h2>Validate input and output</h2>`,
      `<p>AI systems can produce unexpected results, so validation matters. Validate user input before sending it. Limit length. Prevent empty requests. Check required fields. After receiving output, validate the shape if the UI expects structured data. If the response should be JSON, handle parsing failures gracefully.</p>`,
      `<p>Never assume every AI response is ready for production. For content workflows, include a review step. For recommendations, explain that suggestions are guidance. For sensitive domains, add human review and careful disclaimers. Responsible AI integration means designing for uncertainty.</p>`,
      `<h2>Build useful automation</h2>`,
      `<p>Automation is where AI becomes powerful. A content platform can generate drafts, create metadata, save files, commit to GitHub, and trigger deployment. A dashboard can summarize user activity. A booking system can draft confirmation messages. A support tool can categorize requests. These features reduce repeated manual work.</p>`,
      `<p>Automation should include status visibility. Users should know if a job is pending, generating, reviewing, published, or failed. Silent automation is dangerous because users cannot trust what they cannot see. Logs, progress states, retry buttons, and clear messages make automation feel professional.</p>`,
      `<h2>Keep the user in control</h2>`,
      `<p>AI should assist, not trap. Give users edit options. Let them regenerate. Let them copy results. Let them approve before publishing. A good AI interface feels like a capable assistant sitting inside the product. It should speed up the user, not take away their judgment.</p>`,
      `<p>For beginner-focused tools, explain what the AI produced. If a generated article has sections, show the outline. If a recommendation is made, show why. If a prompt template is used, make it understandable. Transparency increases trust.</p>`,
      `<h2>Measure quality manually first</h2>`,
      `<p>Before building complex evaluation systems, manually review outputs. Are they useful? Are they accurate enough? Are they repetitive? Do they match the user’s tone? Can the user act on them? Manual review teaches what quality means for the product. Later, you can add automated checks, moderation, or scoring.</p>`,
      `<h2>Plan the full feature flow</h2>`,
      `<p>An AI feature needs more than an input box and output paragraph. Plan what happens before generation, during generation, after generation, and when generation fails. Before generation, users need examples or clear prompts. During generation, they need loading feedback and the ability to understand that work is happening. After generation, they need editing, saving, sharing, or publishing actions. On failure, they need retry support and a useful message.</p>`,
      `<p>For an automated article product, a strong flow might be: choose category, select audience, enter topic, generate outline, review structure, generate draft, edit content, approve metadata, choose publication time, and view published result. This is far more reliable than sending one large request and immediately placing the returned content on a live website.</p>`,
      `<h2>Backend decisions for AI requests</h2>`,
      `<p>Keep AI API keys on the server. The browser should submit the user request to a protected backend route, and that route should validate the input, call the model service, and return only safe output. Add rate limits or usage controls if the feature is public. Log enough information to debug failures while avoiding private user data in logs.</p>`,
      `<p>Structured output can simplify UI building. If the feature needs a title, excerpt, tags, sections, and publication metadata, request a structured result and validate every field before storing it. If validation fails, retry or ask for review rather than saving malformed content. AI reduces effort only when its output can enter a dependable workflow.</p>`,
      `<h2>Useful AI features for web products</h2>`,
      `<ul><li><strong>Content assistance:</strong> article outlines, service descriptions, social captions, metadata drafts, and readable summaries.</li><li><strong>Workflow assistance:</strong> classify support messages, propose task priorities, or convert notes into structured actions.</li><li><strong>Learning assistance:</strong> interview practice prompts, feedback drafts, coding explanations, and personalized study plans.</li><li><strong>Business assistance:</strong> reply drafting, FAQ suggestions, product recommendations, and customer intent categorization.</li></ul>`,
      `<h2>Trust, review, and originality</h2>`,
      `<p>Content generated with AI still needs ownership. Review facts, remove repetitive language, check links, improve examples, and ensure the output represents the product honestly. A blog should not publish inaccurate claims simply because automation makes publishing fast. Trust is a product feature, especially for educational or income-related topics.</p>`,
      `<p>Used thoughtfully, AI helps a developer build faster and explore more ideas. Used carelessly, it fills products with generic text and uncertain answers. The goal is not to replace creative and technical judgment; it is to give that judgment better tools. That is how AI-powered web applications become valuable, maintainable, and professional.</p>`,
      `<h2>Workshop: create an AI-assisted publishing workflow</h2>`,
      `<p>Begin with a narrowly defined editorial goal, such as practical web-development lessons for beginners. Create a topic form that asks for category, target audience, desired difficulty, and a few required ideas. The server receives those values, validates them, and constructs a structured request. The AI returns an outline first, not a finished published post. This gives the editor control before expensive or low-quality work continues.</p>`,
      `<p>After outline approval, generate a draft with a required title, excerpt, headings, examples, tags, and a conclusion. Store it as a draft rather than publishing instantly. The review screen should allow editing and show warnings if links are missing, text is too short, or unsupported claims appear. Human review is not a failure of automation; it is the part that protects the brand.</p>`,
      `<p>Once approved, the system can schedule publication. A workflow may create the article data file, update a content index, commit to a repository, run the production build, and deploy the result. Record status transitions such as draft, approved, scheduled, publishing, live, and failed. If a step fails, show the editor what happened and allow retry without regenerating everything.</p>`,
      `<p>Readers should receive a complete product experience too. The published article should load quickly, use clear typography, provide a matching image, show category and read time, include related articles, and allow sharing. A simple local like button can add interaction without requiring a user account. The AI feature succeeds only when the final reader experience is useful.</p>`,
      `<h2>Questions to ask before releasing AI functionality</h2>`,
      `<ul><li>Is the use case specific enough that generated output is genuinely helpful?</li><li>Are secrets and generation calls protected on the server?</li><li>Can the user review, edit, reject, or retry the output?</li><li>Does automation expose publishing status and failure handling?</li><li>Would I be comfortable attaching my name or company name to every published result?</li></ul>`,
      practiceLab({
        theme: "an AI-assisted content workflow",
        deliverable: "a draft-generation tool with review, scheduling status, publication controls, and a readable published article page",
        user: "editor preparing useful content",
        decision: "treat AI output as a reviewed draft and keep model requests and secret credentials on the server",
        failure: "generation produces an invalid structure, a weak factual claim, or a publishing job that fails midway",
        proof: "can an editor improve and approve every result while readers receive clear and trustworthy published content?",
        growth: "connecting structured AI drafts to a transparent scheduled publishing and deployment pipeline",
      }),
      `<p>Quality also improves when the review process records decisions. Save the original draft, the edited version, and the reason an editor changed a title, removed a claim, or rewrote an example. Those small observations reveal where prompts need improvement and where human judgment remains essential. Over time, the workflow becomes faster without lowering the standard readers deserve.</p>`,
      `<p>AI integration is not magic. It is product design, backend engineering, prompt design, validation, and user experience combined. Start with one useful workflow. Make it reliable. Give the user control. Then automate carefully. That approach creates AI features that feel helpful instead of noisy.</p>`
    ),
  },
];
